properties.name: xxSOP-00344_Issue Management using JIRA.pdf
properties.short_summary: Objective This SOP is the formal guideline that defines the OpenText standard procedures for all Issue Management using JIRA; its purpose is to support the management of Product Development projects in an agile way.  Additionally, this document is no...
properties.summary: Objective This SOP is the formal guideline that defines the OpenText standard procedures for all Issue Management using JIRA; its purpose is to support the management of Product Development projects in an agile way.  Additionally, this document is not meant to replace the JIRA user manual, it merely describes how the JIRA tool is to be employed in support of the agile development environment; which is defined by the formal guideline set out in the IDP Framework SDLC-00240.  JIRA Concepts Project A JIRA Project is a container used to group all the issues for a product.  Epic - high-level product requirements that need to be broken down further before implementation • UserStory - business requirements • Feature Request – customer and internally reported requests for new or different functionality • Theme - a legacy issue type which can be used to link multiple related issues together.  Support Request – customer situations that require development assistance • Escalation-Sub – a sub-task type for tracking customer requests to fix the parent Bug or Feature Request; also used for the related purpose of tracking work to produce patches fixing the parent issue.

properties.summary: OpenText Content Server forms the document management cornerstone of the OpenText Content Suite and provides secure, enterprise-wide control over any type of content from contracts to engineering drawings, system reports, email messages, images rich media and much more.  OpenText Content Server features fundamental tools such as workflow, offline editing, version control, taxonomy, multilingual metadata categorization, and reporting, and is easily customized and extended with REST API and a Widget Framework that can be used to expose Content Server.  If a website is imported into Content Server, relative links within HTML pages to other pages and images stored in Content Server now work with the Smart View.  Note: Although Content Server Syndication is packaged with Content Server, a valid license must be purchased to use Content Server Syndication on production environments.  The full install package should be used for new installations of Content Server as well as for upgrades from versions of Content Server that require a parallel upgrade (Content Server (Livelink) 9.7.1 UTF-8 and later).

Content Description Visual Elements Audio Text Developer Notes Introduction to Workflow step attachments Video intro When you are assigned a Workflow step that has attachments in OpenText Content Server Smart View, you can add, edit and view the attachments within the Workflow step. properties.summary: Server Specification While Web Viewer supports both Windows and UNIX OS, generally we recommend the use of a supported UNIX OS to host the Web Viewer Server instance.  Document Characteristics TIFF Black &White documents When rendering TIFF B&W documents, the application allocates large block of the memory right in the beginning to minimize the “seek”, “shrink”, and “grow” operations (memory segmentation problem).  Again the application can host rendering tasks for ~5 users in parallel and which can be extrapolated for higher number of users but is limited against constraints of 1.5 GB RAM on x32 Java architecture and number of processors available on the system.  Here is an example worker.properties file to define 3 workers, 2 real workers(Tomcat instances ) using ajp13, the last one being a load balancing worker(Apache web server).  Test and Verification Once the configuration of Apache web server and Tomcat instances is done, start all tomcat instances and Apache web server then you can access the following link on the web server to see the status and configuration details of all the load balanced tomcat instance.

properties.summary: Appending a type character to an identifier that conceptually does not have a type (for example, a namespace name) or to an identifier whose type disagrees with the type of the type character causes a compile-time error.  End Sub End Class End Class Inheritance An inheritance relationship is one in which one type (the derived type) derives from another (the base type), such that the derived type's declaration space implicitly contains the accessible non-constructor type members and nested types of its base type.  If type C is derived from type B, and type B is derived from type A, type C inherits the type members declared in type B as well as the type members declared in type A. A derived type extends, but cannot narrow, its base type.  That is, when a type B derives from a type A, it is an error for type A to derive directly or indirectly from type B. A type may not directly or indirectly derive from a type nested within it.  For each nested namespace containing the name reference, starting from the innermost namespace and going to the outermost namespace: If R matches the name of a nested namespace in the current namespace and no type argument list is supplied, then the unqualified name refers to that nested namespace.

properties.short_summary: Achieving Accessibility in SharePoint 2010 Introduction This document sets out the learning from Vision Australia’s experiences to date delivering an accessible implementation of SharePoint 2010, including our assessment of SharePoint 2010 conformanc...
properties.summary: Achieving Accessibility in SharePoint 2010 Introduction This document sets out the learning from Vision Australia’s experiences to date delivering an accessible implementation of SharePoint 2010, including our assessment of SharePoint 2010 conformance with the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG 2.0).  SharePoint 2010 offers several features, that coupled with appropriate training and strong governance practices, can support content authors throughout an organisation to create accessible web content and ensure that accessibility conformance is maintained: • Use tools such as the Accessibility Checker built into Word 2010.  Overall Conclusions and Recommendations Our conclusions in this analysis are as follows: • Significant progress has been made with out of the box accessibility in SharePoint 2010 and with appropriate customisation and governance decisions we believe SharePoint 2010 can achieve WCAG 2.0 Double A conformance.  In a distributed content environment, SharePoint 2010 offers features that assist with maintaining accessibility conformance including the ability to manage accessibility through deploying a specific set of conforming master pages and web components; the accessibility checker in Office 2010; and defining workflows to manage content approval processes.  Useful links about accessibility and SharePoint 2010: • Web Content Accessibility Guidelines version 2.0 detailed reference to WCAG 2.0 including supporting materials – ‘how to meet WCAG 2.0’, ‘understanding WCAG 2.0’ and ‘techniques for WCAG 2.0’.

properties.summary: About this Document.  This reference documentation targets both new users of OTSelenium IDE and those who have been using OTSelenium IDE and are seeking additional knowledge.  It compiles in one place a set of useful Selenium techniques and best practices by drawing from the knowledge of multiple experienced Selenium QA professionals, Open Text Content Server Automation team’s QA developers and CS Automation QA professionals.  This section introduces OTSelenium IDE, and step-by-step instruction for how to build automation test cases, and run the test cases in different tools.  Running Test Cases Using Different Tools Running Test Cases using OTSelenium IDE Running Test Cases using OTSelenium RC Player Running Test Cases using OTTR.

properties.summary: Current Available Autobot Commands.  When using the Autobot commands with Selenium and Ottr, the following variables should be used in your custom User Extension JavaScript file.  When trying to run existing test cases that require autobot and use variables that are stored in a user extension file, this must be added to your local machine.  The variable {CTSR_HOST_PATH} is a variable that is defined in the custom user extesntion file that points to the IP address of where Autobot is installed and the port which it was installed on.  Add Section & Option To INI File: The following example adds a section namesd "Test" to the INI file with an option "OpenTextAutoBot" that has the value of "123".
